'''LBRY''' is a [[blockchain]]-based [[File sharing|file-sharing]] and payment network that powers [[Decentralized application|decentralized]] platforms, primarily [[social networks]] and [[Online video platform|video platforms]]. LBRY's creators also run '''Odysee''', a video-sharing website that uses the network.<ref name=":2" /> Video platforms built on LBRY, such as Odysee, have been described as decentralized alternatives to [[YouTube]].<ref name=":0" /> The company has described Odysee and other platforms it has built utilizing its LBRY protocol as platforms for [[Freedom of speech|free speech]] and lightly moderates content, including removing pornography or the promotion of violence and terrorism.<ref name=":2" />

== Technology ==
The LBRY protocol is a decentralized file-sharing and payment network built using blockchain and [[BitTorrent]] technology.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|last=Prakash|first=Abhishek|date=April 5, 2020|title=LBRY: A Blockchain-based Decentralized YouTube Alternative|url=https://itsfoss.com/lbry/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210124003634/https://itsfoss.com/lbry/|archive-date=January 24, 2021|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=It's FOSS|language=en-US}}</ref> It allows anyone to create an account and register content that cannot be deleted by the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ovide|first=Shira|date=January 26, 2021|title=What is a Blockchain? Is It Hype?|language=en-US|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/26/technology/what-is-blockchain.html|url-status=live|access-date=January 29, 2021|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=January 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210128164733/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/26/technology/what-is-blockchain.html}}</ref> LBRY uses BitTorrent technology to serve content without relying on their own servers by using [[peer-to-peer]] file-sharing.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|last=Hackett|first=Robert|last2=Morris|first2=David Z.|date=January 27, 2021|title=Tesla, GameStop, and the power of 'meme stocks'|url=https://fortune.com/2021/01/27/gamestop-stock-gme-shares-tesla-tsla-elon-musk-meme-stocksshort-squeeze/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210127223439/https://fortune.com/2021/01/27/gamestop-stock-gme-shares-tesla-tsla-elon-musk-meme-stocksshort-squeeze/|archive-date=January 27, 2021|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|language=en}}</ref> Creators can record video content to the LBRY blockchain, as well as other digital content including music, images, [[podcast]]s, and [[e-book]]s.<ref name=":3" /> The LBRY projects are [[open source]].<ref name=":3" />

In October 2017, LBRY, Inc. released a media hosting site built atop the protocol called spee.ch.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|last=Slattery|first=Brinck|date=October 30, 2017|title=Always GIF Responsibly: Introducing Spee.ch|url=https://lbry.com/news/always-gif-responsibly|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123182546/https://lbry.com/news/always-gif-responsibly|archive-date=January 23, 2021|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=LBRY|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news|last=Hanrahan|first=Jake|date=May 20, 2019|title=3D-printed guns are back, and this time they are unstoppable|language=en-GB|work=[[Wired UK]]|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/3d-printed-guns-blueprints|url-status=live|access-date=January 29, 2021|issn=1357-0978|archive-date=February 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210216200558/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/3d-printed-guns-blueprints}}</ref> It stopped being supported in December 2019, in favor of LBRY, Inc.'s LBRY.tv website.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|last=Zarebczan|first=Thomas|date=December 8, 2019|title=lbryio/spee.ch@ad87e2b|url=https://github.com/lbryio/spee.ch/commit/ad87e2b8a7c793b00b6a83b2bfffd44ce7fcd48b|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=[[GitHub]]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":4" /> Odysee, another video website built by LBRY, Inc. using their LBRY protocol, entered [[Software release life cycle|beta]] in September 2020 and officially launched that December.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|last=Ha|first=Anthony|date=December 7, 2020|title=Odysee aims to build a more independent video platform|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/12/07/odysee-launch/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=[[TechCrunch]]|language=en-US}}</ref>

LBRY, Inc. also maintains their own [[cryptocurrency]], "LBRY credits" (LBC), which they use as a part of a digital store they have built based on the LBRY blockchain. Using this currency, creators can charge viewers to stream their content or earn [[Gratuity|tips]]. Users of the platform earn LBC through using the platform and inviting others to it.<ref name=":3" /> On March 29, 2021, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) charged LBRY, Inc. with selling unregistered digital asset securities.<ref name=":9">{{Cite web|last=Matthews|first=Chris|date=April 7, 2021|title=Blockchain firm LBRY tries to rally sector against SEC; critics allege a 'cryptocurrency suppression program'|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/blockchain-firm-lbry-tries-to-rally-sector-against-sec-critics-allege-a-cryptocurrency-suppression-program-11617807779|url-status=live|access-date=April 9, 2021|website=[[MarketWatch]]|language=en-US|archive-date=April 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210408070439/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/blockchain-firm-lbry-tries-to-rally-sector-against-sec-critics-allege-a-cryptocurrency-suppression-program-11617807779}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=March 29, 2021|title=SEC Charges New Hampshire Issuer of Digital Asset Securities with Registration Violations|publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2021/lr25060.htm|access-date=April 9, 2021|archive-date=April 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210402130801/https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2021/lr25060.htm|url-status=live}}</ref> The SEC alleged that LBRY, Inc. had sold LBRY credits (LBC) to fund their work without registering them with the SEC as a security, a violation of securities laws. In response, LBRY's CEO began a public relations campaign to gather support among blockchain and cryptocurrency enthusiasts, and to argue that the SEC had mislabeled LBC as a security.<ref name=":9" />

== Content and users ==
The LBRY platform's video sharing websites have been described as an alternative to YouTube.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|last=Popper|first=Nathaniel|author-link=Nathaniel Popper|date=January 28, 2021|title=They found a way to limit Big Tech's power: Using the design of Bitcoin|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/26/technology/big-tech-power-bitcoin.html|url-status=live|access-date=January 29, 2021|archive-date=May 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210502164528/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/26/technology/big-tech-power-bitcoin.html}}</ref> spee.ch, a media hosting site built atop the LBRY protocol, was used by groups such as [[Deterrence Dispensed]] to upload [[3D printed firearm]] blueprints.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":5" /> When LBRY, Inc. stopped supporting spee.ch in 2019 in favor of their new site, LBRY.tv, Deterrence Dispensed moved to LBRY.tv.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=Deterrence Dispensed|url=https://www.deterrencedispensed.com/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210128170204/https://www.deterrencedispensed.com/|archive-date=January 28, 2021|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=|language=en-US}}</ref>

The LBRY platform experienced a surge in popularity in late 2020 and early 2021, and LBRY, Inc. said in January 2021 that their new user sign-ups had increased 250% from the previous month. Writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'',  [[Nathaniel Popper]] reported that many of the new users appeared to be supporters of former United States president [[Donald Trump]], [[White supremacy|white supremacists]], and [[Gun politics in the United States|gun rights advocates]] who were suspended from YouTube.<ref name=":0" /> Robert Hackett and David Z. Morris writing for ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' attributed the increased interest in LBRY and other blockchain-based platforms to the choice by [[Twitter]] and other popular social networks to ban Trump and many others after the [[2021 United States Capitol attack]].<ref name=":1" />

{{As of|2021|4}}, Odysee hosted 10{{Nbsp}}million videos, the most-viewed of which was a video questioning the safety of [[COVID-19 vaccine]]s.<ref name=":11">{{Cite web|last=Bookman|first=Todd|date=April 19, 2021|title=From Cooking Videos to QAnon, N.H.-Based Video Platform Attracts Users Banned Elsewhere|url=https://www.nhpr.org/post/cooking-videos-qanon-nh-based-video-platform-attracts-users-banned-elsewhere|url-status=live|access-date=May 31, 2021|website=[[New Hampshire Public Radio]]|language=en|archive-date=June 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602214613/https://www.nhpr.org/post/cooking-videos-qanon-nh-based-video-platform-attracts-users-banned-elsewhere}}</ref> A May 2021 report by ''[[The Guardian]]'' found "scores of extremist videos" on the Odysee platform that promoted [[Antisemitic canard|antisemitic conspiracy theories]], glorified [[Adolf Hitler]] and other Nazis, shared [[COVID-19 misinformation]], and depicted meetings and rallies by extremist groups including the white nationalist and antisemitic National Justice party and the neo-Nazi [[Nordic Resistance Movement]].<ref name=":10">{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Jason|date=May 14, 2021|title=Video platform chief says Nazi posts on white superiority do not merit removal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/may/14/odysee-video-platform-nazi-content-not-grounds-for-removal|url-status=live|access-date=May 14, 2021|website=[[The Guardian]]|language=en|archive-date=May 14, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514102804/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/may/14/odysee-video-platform-nazi-content-not-grounds-for-removal}}</ref>

[[Megan Squire]], a computer scientist and researcher of right-wing political extremism, described challenges faced by blockchains such as LBRY and the social networks built atop them: "As a technology it is very cool, but you can't just sit there and be a [[Pollyanna principle|Pollyanna]] and think that all information will be free&nbsp;... There will be racists, and people will shoot each other. It's going to be the total package."<ref name=":0" /> Extremism researcher Eviane Leidig, writing for the Global Network on Extremism & Technology (GNET) at [[The International Centre for the Study of Radicalisation and Political Violence]], described Odysee as "the new YouTube for the far-right", and wrote that although Odysee was "not inherently a platform for far-right or extremist content creators", it had become popular among them.<ref name=":13">{{Cite web|last=Leidig|first=Eviane|date=February 17, 2021|title=Odysee: The New YouTube for the Far-Right|url=https://gnet-research.org/2021/02/17/odysee-the-new-youtube-for-the-far-right/|url-status=live|access-date=May 31, 2021|website=Global Network on Extremism & Technology|publisher=[[The International Centre for the Study of Radicalisation and Political Violence]]|language=en-GB|archive-date=June 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210602214210/https://gnet-research.org/2021/02/17/odysee-the-new-youtube-for-the-far-right/}}</ref>

== Moderation ==
Because the LBRY network is built on a blockchain, there is no way for LBRY, Inc. to moderate at the blockchain level their users or the content that they upload.<ref name=":0" /> LBRY, Inc. is able to moderate content on the websites they build on top of the protocol.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|last=O'Sullivan|first=Andrea|date=February 23, 2021|title=The Best Way for Florida to 'Take on Big Tech' Is to Keep Welcoming the Crypto Community|url=https://reason.com/2021/02/23/the-best-way-for-florida-to-take-on-big-tech-is-to-keep-welcoming-the-crypto-community/|url-status=live|access-date=March 5, 2021|website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|language=en-US|archive-date=February 26, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226041420/https://reason.com/2021/02/23/the-best-way-for-florida-to-take-on-big-tech-is-to-keep-welcoming-the-crypto-community/}}</ref> On LBRY's Odysee platform, guidelines prohibit content including [[pornography]] and promotion of violence or terrorism.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" /> Rule-breaking content can be delisted from Odysee, which leaves the channel and content in place and continues to allow it to be shared, but prevents it from being found via search or browsing channels.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Brown|first=Eileen|date=April 8, 2021|title=Blockchain-based Odysee keeps your social media content online|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/blockchain-based-odysee-keeps-your-social-media-content-online/|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2021|website=[[ZDNet]]|language=en|archive-date=April 12, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210412160827/https://www.zdnet.com/article/blockchain-based-odysee-keeps-your-social-media-content-online/}}</ref> Most people access the protocol through the LBRY platform: websites including Odysee and LBRY.tv which are built on top of the LBRY blockchain.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" />

Todd Bookman writing for [[New Hampshire Public Radio]] described Odysee's approach to content moderation as "no censorship, no-[[deplatforming]], no matter what users say."<ref name=":11" /> When asked in July 2019 about the use of LBRY, Inc.'s sites to host blueprints for 3D printed guns, LBRY, Inc.'s CEO Kauffman has said that he would only remove the files from his websites if courts deem them illegal. Champe Barton writing for ''[[The Trace (website)|The Trace]]'' has said Kauffman "signal[ed] his support" for the distribution of such blueprints by sharing them on his personal Twitter account.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|last=Barton|first=Champe|date=July 25, 2019|title=As Social Networks Crack Down, 3D-Printed Gun Community Moves to New Platforms|url=https://www.thetrace.org/2019/07/3d-printed-guns-social-media-ban/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210203084646/https://www.thetrace.org/2019/07/3d-printed-guns-social-media-ban/|archive-date=February 3, 2021|access-date=January 29, 2021|website=[[The Trace (website)|The Trace]]|language=en-us}}</ref> Kauffman criticized YouTube's content policies in December 2020 as "far too strict", pointing to the platform's decision to remove an interview with [[Scott Atlas]], formerly a healthcare policy advisor to the Trump administration, that allegedly contained [[Misinformation related to the COVID-19 pandemic|COVID-19 misinformation]].<ref name=":2" />  On May 14, 2021, ''The Guardian'' reported that LBRY executive Julian Chandra wrote to Odysee site moderators that a "Nazi that makes videos about the superiority of the white race" was not grounds for removal from Odysee. The email was accidentally sent to a user who had complained about neo-Nazi content on the platform.<ref name=":10" />

== Company ==
LBRY, Inc., which builds the LBRY protocol and the platform based upon it, was founded in May 2015 by Jeremy Kauffman and Jimmy Kiselak.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":12">{{Cite web|last=Kauffman|first=Jeremy|date=May 24, 2015|title=The LBRY Opens|url=https://lbry.com/news/the-lbry-opens|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123175001/https://lbry.com/news/the-lbry-opens|archive-date=January 23, 2021|access-date=2021-01-29|website=LBRY|language=en}}</ref> The company is based in [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], New Hampshire.<ref name=":11" /> Both the company name and the LBRY project are pronounced "library".<ref name=":2" />

Through 2015 and 2016, Kauffman and Kiselak were joined by Mike Vine, Josh Finer, and Alex Grintsvayg, who they also described as co-founders.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Vine|first=Mike|date=October 22, 2015|title=Mike Vine Joins LBRY as Technology Evangelist|url=https://lbry.com/news/mike-vine-joins-lbry-as-technology-evangelist-2|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123175401/https://lbry.com/news/mike-vine-joins-lbry-as-technology-evangelist-2|archive-date=January 23, 2021|access-date=2021-01-29|website=LBRY|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Bryan|first=Samuel|date=January 6, 2016|title=LBRY Means Business With Addition of Josh Finer, MBA|url=https://lbry.com/news/lbry-adds-chief-growth-officer-josh-finer|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123171153/https://lbry.com/news/lbry-adds-chief-growth-officer-josh-finer|archive-date=January 23, 2021|access-date=2021-01-29|website=LBRY|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite web|last=Bryan|first=Samuel|date=June 7, 2016|title=New Core Teammate Is An Ultimate Wizard: Meet Grin|url=https://lbry.com/news/ultimate-wizard-meet-alex-grin|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210203180430/https://lbry.com/news/ultimate-wizard-meet-alex-grin|archive-date=February 3, 2021|access-date=2021-01-29|website=LBRY|language=en}}</ref> Kauffman, Kiselak, and Grintsvayg all attended [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], where they played [[Ultimate (sport)|ultimate frisbee]] together.<ref name=":8" /> Kauffman remains LBRY's [[chief executive officer]], Grintsvayg is [[chief technology officer]], and Finer is the director of operations and analytics.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=The Team|url=https://lbry.com/team|access-date=2021-01-29|website=LBRY|language=en|archive-date=February 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201122626/https://lbry.com/team|url-status=live}}</ref> Julian Chandra is the company's [[chief marketing officer]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Romaine|first=Jenna|date=May 14, 2021|title=Social media executive says Nazi posts on white superiority should not be removed|url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/553544-social-media-executive-says-nazi-posts-on-white-superiority|url-status=live|access-date=May 31, 2021|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|language=en|quote=[Chandra] also clarified his title as chief marketing officer, not vice president of growth.|archive-date=May 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210528030541/https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/553544-social-media-executive-says-nazi-posts-on-white-superiority}}</ref>

